{{Infobox feature on Mars
|name=Ganges Chasma
|image=[[Image:Ganges Chasma (Themis Day).png|200px]]
|caption=Ganges Chasma, as seen by [[Thermal Emission Imaging System|THEMIS]].
|coordinates= {{coord|8.0|S|48.1|W|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}
|length=584.0 km
}}
'''Ganges Chasma''' is a deep [[canyon]] at the eastern end of the vast [[Valles Marineris]] system on [[Mars]], an offshoot of [[Capri Chasma]], and is in the [[Coprates quadrangle]].  It is named after the [[River Ganges]] in South Asia. Ganges Chasma is thought to have formed through a series of catastrophic discharges of water and CO<sub>2</sub> from chaos terrains such as that preserved in Ganges Chaos at its southern margin.<ref name="RodriguezKargel2006">{{cite journal|last1=Rodriguez|first1=J. A. P.|last2=Kargel|first2=J.|last3=Crown|first3=D. A.|last4=Bleamaster|first4=L. F.|last5=Tanaka|first5=K. L.|last6=Baker|first6=V.|last7=Miyamoto|first7=H.|last8=Dohm|first8=J. M.|last9=Sasaki|first9=S.|last10=Komatsu|first10=G.|title=Headward growth of chasmata by volatile outbursts, collapse, and drainage: Evidence from Ganges chaos, Mars|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|volume=33|issue=18|date=September 2006|issn=0094-8276|doi=10.1029/2006GL026275|bibcode=2006GeoRL..3318203R}}</ref> Most of the evidence for these discharges and the ensuing collapses is believed to have been washed away.<ref name="RodriguezKargel2006"/> Prior to developing an outlet that joined it to Capri Chasma and the connected [[outflow channels]] to its east, Ganges Chasma may at some point in the [[Noachian]] period have contained a lake which drained northward through partially subsurface pathways into [[Shalbatana Vallis]].<ref name="Rodriguez2003">{{cite journal|last1=Rodriguez|first1=J. A. P.|last2=Sasaki|first2=S.|last3=Miyamoto|first3=H.|title=Nature and hydrological relevance of the Shalbatana complex underground cavernous system|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|volume=30|issue=6|year=2003|issn=0094-8276|doi=10.1029/2002GL016547|bibcode=2003GeoRL..30.1304R}}</ref>

