'''Peter James de Lange''' (born 1966) is a [[New Zealand]] [[botanist]]. He graduated from the [[University of Waikato]] as [[Bachelor of Science|B.Sc.]] in biological and earth sciences then as [[Master of Science|M.Sc.]] in [[paleoecology]] and [[Geochronology|tephrochronostratigraphy]]. He has a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the [[University of Auckland]], the subject of his [[thesis]], the biosystematics of ''[[Kunzea ericoides]]''. Since 1990 he has worked as a threatened plant scientist in the Ecosystems and Species Unit of Research and Development in the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|New Zealand Department of Conservation]]. He is a [[Linnean Society of London|Fellow of the Linnean Society]] and is the author of 14 books and 120 scientific papers.<ref name="museum">{{cite web|title=Peter J. de Lange|url=http://kermadec.aucklandmuseum.com/expedition-team/peter-j-de-lange/|publisher=Auckland Museum|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref name="unitec">{{cite web|title=Dr Peter de Lange|url=http://www.unitec.ac.nz/about-us/contact-us/staff-directory/dr-peter-de-lange|publisher=Unitec Institute of Technology Auckland|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref name="DOC">{{cite web|title=Why botany matters: Peter DeLange|url=https://blog.doc.govt.nz/2017/07/07/why-botany-matters-peter-delange/|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>

